Hello Matic, I was wondering if I could talk to anyone from your engineering team. I have a smart contract game which is a series of gamified ERC20’s and would want to maintain the ability for users to bring those tokens back to Ethereum mainnet. Whenever this happens, any transfers occuring on ETh would still need to update supply variables existing on Matic. I am just wondering if this is all possible. Please let me know.
@Josophy does the issue still persist?
GG @Angela (IST), you just advanced to level 5!
@Deleted User yes that should be possible. One question though: would you want your tokens to be minted on matic or ethereum?

@Angela (IST)  thanks for your response! Minting of tokens is part of the game, so it should happen on Matic. But... whenever tokens are transferred, a percentage is "burned/returned" and the supply variables would need to be updated. For the token to remain authentic, this functionality would need to persist whenever the token is transferred within main-net. But the supply variables on Matic would need to be updated with each ETH tx. Sorry if this is confusing.

at the same time, movement from Matic to ETH (and vice-versa) should not experience deflation (since the token is staying with the same user), but I think this can be easily fixed with an alternate transfer function specifically for the bridge.

Hi I'm researching on Matic and reading the blow article.https://blog.matic.network/explaining-plasma-and-rollups-advantages-and-limitations-matic-network/In the middle of the content, there is a calculation like below. Could anyone tell me where the number 8750 came up from?Mass exitsThe primary contention about mass exits in Plasma is that if there is a sufficiently large number of users performing mass exit, it can lead to congestion on mainchain (Ethereum) and users may not be able to exit in time. Sure, mass exits can be big in size, but how big?Let’s use an example for illustration.Assume- Number of users on the sidechain, u = 100,000,- Gas required for MoreVP exit, g = 700,000,- y is the fraction of Ethereum block filled for mass exits alone. 0 < y <= 1Then- Roughly for 100k users, you would need 8750/y blocks on Ethereum to execute the mass exit.

So if I am getting this correct, Users send MATIC to  DepositManagerProxy0x401F6c983eA34274ec46f84D70b31C151321188bThis contract acts as an escrow contract where the assets are held for future use on the MATIC network.Would I also be correct in saying that this contract  facilitates state changes from rootChain  onto the childChain's?I.e funds deposited in the DepositManagerProxy are then used to mint ERC20/721 on childChain?

@Anurag I truly appreciate you taking the time to help and to guide.  You, the admins do a sterling service for the community.  Thank you.Anyway, I’m wondering if you could just run your eyes over the following work flow to see if I understand what is happeningInitially tokens/assets are sent to the DepositManagerProxy contract0x401F6c983eA34274ec46f84D70b31C151321188bThis is in essence an escrow contract which holds assets until they are withdrawn from the MATIC network.From there, assets undergo a state change, for further use on the MATIC network.   This state change is carried out using the of state sync process. The state-sync mechanism is basically a way to move state data from the Ethereum chain to Bor.State sync, uses a contract called the state receiver contract.  The state receiver contract manages incoming state sync records.  Assets that undergo state change are essentially minted to ERC20/721 token contracts and free for use on childChains?This is where I get a little confused. > Developer question :> > I've been reading this https://docs.matic.network/docs/develop/advanced/swap-assets#transferwithsig-method> > And I think there is a possibility of front-running attack here, because to is not included in the dataHash, so someone watching for this method call could front-run and change the recipient of the transaction with the same signature> > Is this possible or am I overseeing something?@dievardump the data hash is constructed inside using msg.sender. If somebody wants to frontrun it - msg.sender will be different and ecrecovery will fail. Basically if msg.sender will be different from the one who was approved to spend - instant fail.

messages.content: Are there any rough estimates of the security of the PoS portal? We've been working on integrating our Dapp with Matic for the last couple of days. Currently we're using the PoS bridge for depositing and withdrawing ETH, mainly because the 7 day challenge period is not required for withdrawing. I just have zero intuition what the probability of failure is when using PoS instead of plasma.

The PoS bridge is run by the Matic validators - each deposit or withdraw transaction is dependent on 2/3 majority PBFT consensus amongst the validators. 2/3 consensus is based on weighted stake. Staking is managed on Ethereum contracts.Currently as on date, ~$23mn+ worth of MATIC tokens have been staked by validators and delegators for the right to run these validator nodes. There are 75 validators on the mainnet currently, which will increase to 100 in a couple of months.Validators will be subject to slashing in case of downtime and misbehavior such as double-spending - this feature is not enabled currently but will be turned on soon based on validator governance.

Choose MAX if you want to swap all of your WETH4) This process consists of 2 transactions : Approve and Swap5) The first transaction is Approve. You will have to confirm this transaction from your connected wallet.6) Now click on Continue. You will be asked to sign another transaction.7) Once confirmed, you will soon receive the equivalent PoS-WETH ( For now, you will receive same amount of PoS WETH as your WETH )8) PoS WETH can be used in https://matic.opensea.io/ and other dapps In the future, please follow this tutorial to deposit ETH from Ethereum to get PoS-WETHhttps://docs.matic.network/docs/develop/wallets/matic-web-wallet/deposit-eth-dai-on-maticAlso, you can follow this https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1x-Dvg9oxLo  video tutorial to understand how to get funds and trade on https://matic.opensea.io/Hope this help 🙂

messages.content: WTF? Hello, you nor ANY team member of Polygon NOR any project in ANY capacity should be encouraging users to share their addresses in a public space like this. It's called a "public address" but it does not mean that users want to freely connect their accounts to their identities in a public forum like this.
ty!

Here's how I recommend you handle support in a public channel, @Parvez:* If it's a simple question that can be answered, you answer it or direct them to where they can find the answer.* If it's something that requires a deeper look and you need to know their transaction hash or address, you ask them to DM it to you or open a support ticket through a private channel like a support email service or something else.* **You should never ask users to post potentially sensitive information in a public space.** How do you know if something is potentially sensitive? Well, if even one person would be uncomfortable sharing something, you can safely consider it sensitive for everyone else as well.* Any platform in the industry should discourage the sharing of sensitive information and should encourage personal OpSec, and that goes 100x for a protocol like Polygon because $ is involved.I understand that it's easier for you if users simply share their info here for you to quickly check, but it's a bad habit for you and for users, and is a bad look for Polygon (and I really love your platform and I'm a bagholder as well). I also understand that DMs can add a level of complication and security risk (due to fake accounts), so if a user has an issue with sensitive info attached and you're uncomfortable receiving DMs, you should direct them to the proper *private* support channel that I hope Polygon has.

messages.content: When I have seen that error I have found that jacking up the gas limit in metamask by 10% or so often fixes the problem. (No need to change the gas fee.) This seems to happen more often when the network is a bit busy as apparently Metamask can misestimate the required gas. Also you may note that when the transaction succeeds, the actual gas used ends up being less than the original limit. So something very strange is happening in those internal transactions.
